<div id="review_427131169" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/427131169" />
    <a title="Jeni" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/649008-jeni"><img alt="Jeni" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563531149p2/649008.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/427131169?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeni" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeni" href="/user/show/649008-jeni">Jeni</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer427131169" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10407285829497016082">This was a long book. Too often, I find myself disappointed when I get to the end of a story; having grown to know the characters, becoming interested in the created community beyond the immediate concerns of the plot and just enjoying the ride. Ms. George&apos;s Inspector Lynley books are becoming longer, it seems, with each new installment. Yet I am reading them as fast as I can. The characters are believable and presented warts and all (sometimes exploring their faults more than their strengths). </span>
  <span id="freeText10407285829497016082" style="display:none">This was a long book. Too often, I find myself disappointed when I get to the end of a story; having grown to know the characters, becoming interested in the created community beyond the immediate concerns of the plot and just enjoying the ride. Ms. George's Inspector Lynley books are becoming longer, it seems, with each new installment. Yet I am reading them as fast as I can. The characters are believable and presented warts and all (sometimes exploring their faults more than their strengths). This one was a bit surprising since the relationship between Lynley and Havers is strained, and neither one reacts as I would expect. <br /><br />I would say the mystery aspect of the plot almost takes a backseat to the exploration of motives, prejudices, and the tendency to fail to see the big picture when we hone in on what we think is the truth.<br /><br />I am very impressed with the author's use of language - I usually have to look up at least one word in the dictionary while reading her books. Also, the British verbiage is remarkable, seeing as the author is an American. The slang, dialects and phrases really keep you rooted in the UK. It does not have the feel of a mystery set in a generic location, with British place names inserted. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10407285829497016082" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


