    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2409995009" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2409995009" />
    <a title="Paula Dembeck" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15166873-paula-dembeck"><img alt="Paula Dembeck" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2409995009?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paula Dembeck" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paula Dembeck" href="/user/show/15166873-paula-dembeck">Paula Dembeck</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2409995009" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3303171346561156745">In this tenth addition to the Inspector Lynley series, George quickly presents the reader with three bodies to think about in less than sixty pages. The first is a suicide. Why did David King-Ryder kill himself after the opening night of his wildly successful production of a musical after years of failure. There was no note to explain his actions. He had simply put a gun to his head and pulled the trigger while his wife was having a bath in the next room. <br/><br/>Then there are the bodies of a young man</span>
  <span id="freeText3303171346561156745" style="display:none">In this tenth addition to the Inspector Lynley series, George quickly presents the reader with three bodies to think about in less than sixty pages. The first is a suicide. Why did David King-Ryder kill himself after the opening night of his wildly successful production of a musical after years of failure. There was no note to explain his actions. He had simply put a gun to his head and pulled the trigger while his wife was having a bath in the next room. <br /><br />Then there are the bodies of a young man and a woman found out on Calder Moor in the ancient circle of stones known as Nine Sisters Henge. Each met a violent and gruesome death, but died in different ways. Their deaths in the Derbyshire countryside are being investigated by Detective Inspector Peter Hanken from the local constabulary until Andy Maiden, the father of one of the victims, puts in a request to New Scotland Yard to have his former colleague Detective Inspector Thomas Lynley assist the investigation. Maiden was an officer in SO10 The Crimes Operation Group, an elite undercover unit and at one time Lynley regarded him as a mentor. Maiden’s request is highly irregular and so Lynley predicts this may be a very fragile and difficult case. It puts him in a sensitive position investigating a case in a district in which he has no authority. At the same time Peter Hanken is not happy having New Scotland Yard on his patch and annoyed that this man from London has been thrust upon him. He did not ask for help and wonders if his competence is in question. <br /><br />Together the two work to identify the young man murdered near Nicola Maiden. No one recognizes him, their only clue is a motorbike left beside Nicola’s car. Was this young man a friend or had Nicola been followed?<br /><br />As Lynley digs into the case he discovers that Andy’s daughter led a life that her parents knew nothing about. He and D.I. Hanken must determine if Andy’s daughter was killed by enemies of her father, someone seeking revenge and anxious to deal out retribution to settle a score or if she had enemies she earned herself in the secret life she chose to lead. <br /><br />This novel follows quickly from events in the previous book when Lynley and Lady Helen finally tied the knot and Sergeant Barabara Havers returned home to rest following her injuries on the last case they had worked together. During her sick leave and while Lynley was away with Helen, Barbara had helped Detective Inspector Emily Barlow with an investigation, but her behavior during that time has her in big trouble with the Yard. As the book opens, Inspector Lynley has just returned from his honeymoon and Barbara has completed a three month suspension from work while her superiors investigated her conduct and determined her future. The charges included assault, attempted murder, abuse of authority and failure to obey an order. They are very serious and threaten her career. Police work has been Havers’ life and she can’t imagine a world without it. <br /><br />After the Police Complaints Department complete their investigation, her superior places scathing letters permanently on her file, delivers a scathing commentary on her behavior and demotes her. Havers feels a sense of betrayal. She feels strongly that she had no choice except to do what she did, but that is not how it has been viewed by those in power. But worse is Detective Lynley’s reaction. She thought he would be on her side but soon learns he agrees with the result of the inquiry. He has tried to understand her point of view but has trouble managing it. He believes firmly in the chain of command and cannot sanction her abuse of it. His reaction has created a wall between them and they are on very fragile footing. Lynley advises Havers to lie low as she is ostracized by her colleagues and shoulders demotion and disgrace. The final blow is the dissolution of her partnership with Lynley, who chooses Detective Constable Winston Nkata to be his partner in the investigation in Derbyshire. This gives readers an opportunity to get to know this character, a former street thug turned police officer, so much better. He is quick, a self-starter and a competent investigator. Given the opportunity to fast track his career because of the rift between Lynley and Havers he chooses a more honorable route using every opportunity he has to help the two mend fences. <br /><br />The investigation poses many questions apart from the identity of the young man who died with Nicola out on the moor . What was he doing there? And what do the papers mean that were scattered around the scene of the crime? There are even more interesting questions about Nicola. Why did she leave law school abruptly without telling tell her parents? And how did Nicola ever afford the high end wardrobe and the electronics they found in her flat? <br /><br />Once again George presents the readers with a full cast of characters, all plausible and convincing suspects in the crime. She is a master at leading her readers down paths that make them believe they know the guilty parties and how events unfolded. Among those potential suspects is Julian Britton, Nicola’s lover for many years who wished to marry her. He is a young man determined to hold on to Broughton Manor, the huge estate his father Jeremy Britton inherited. At one time the manor and estate was a showpiece, but now it has been driven into the ground as his father, desperately short of funds and held back by a lifetime of drinking has ignored the upkeep. His son Julian has been forced to sell much of the art, paintings and antiques to try to make repairs and make ends meet. His cousin Samantha has come to help with the work of cleaning up the buildings and the grounds so Julian can fulfill his dreams of transforming the derelict estate into a thriving business. And Samantha, who never liked Nicola, has her own dreams and a firm conviction to see them realized. Even Jeremy, Julian’s father seems to be forever plotting in the background despite the facts he drinks from morning to night. <br /><br />George’s novels are never quick reads and some readers may become impatient at the level of detail she gives her readers. Her novels are as much about those trying to solve the crime as the crime itself. Like many of her plots, this one is complex as well as intriguing. Given the book’s length, I was surprised at the speed with which she tied up the entire case. It was just too abrupt, wrapped up quickly after George had delivered so many pages detailing possible scenarios and pointing fingers at possible suspects. It was too much too fast. <br /><br />But once again this is a very enjoyable read adding a solid contribution to this ongoing and very successful series. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3303171346561156745" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

